  <title>Reading: Basis</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            ([ILA]) Margalit, Rabinoff, Williams. <pubtitle><url href="https://personal.math.ubc.ca/~tbjw/ila/">Interactive Linear Algebra</url></pubtitle>, UBC ed.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
      Read <section-mark/><section-mark/>3.3<ndash/>3.5. Only a small part is really necessary, and you can rely on the following summaries.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection>
    <title>Linear subspaces</title>
    <p>
      Things have types. Rose is a kind of flower, red is a kind of color, and 3 is a number. Number, <m>n</m>-Vector, and (<m> m \mathord{\times} n </m>)-Matrix are all different types.
    </p>
    <p>
      Operations require specific types. We can <q>put a rose next to a violet</q> but not <q>put a rose next to red</q>: the operation <q>put X next to Y</q> requires both X and Y are concrete objects in reality. Things like
      <me>
        \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix}, \qquad
        \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix}, \qquad
        \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix} + 7
      </me>
      make sense while
      <me>
        \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \\ 6 \\ 7 \end{bmatrix}, \qquad
        \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \\ 6 \\ 7 \end{bmatrix}, \qquad
        \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 8 \\ 9 \end{bmatrix}
      </me>
      are ungrammatical since
      <md>
        <mrow> +:
          \begin{cases}
          ( \text{Number}, \text{Number} ) \to \text{Number} \\
          ( n\text{-Vector}, n\text{-Vector} ) \to n\text{-Vector},
          \end{cases}
        </mrow>
        <mrow> \cdot: ( n\text{-Vector}, n\text{-Vector} ) \to \text{Number} </mrow>
      </md>.
      Type errors are worse than false statements like <q><m> 1 + 1 = 3 </m></q>: in the latter the statement is at least clear though not true.
    </p>
    <p>
      Some types support linear operations, <ie/> adding and scaling:
      <md>
        <mrow> + : ( \text{Type}, \text{Type} ) \to \text{Type}, </mrow>
        <mrow> \cdot \text{ (or omitted) } : ( \text{Number}, \text{Type} ) \to \text{Type} </mrow>
      </md>.
      Number, <m>n</m>-Vector, and (<m> m \mathord{\times} n </m>)-Matrix are all examples. They form linear spaces (now called vector spaces). In particular, <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> is a vector space.
    </p>
    <p>
      If a subset of a vector space is a vector space itself, the subset is then called a linear subspace of the bigger vector space. This means linear operations don't move things originally in the subset outside.
    </p>
    <p>
      A span is a subspace: <eg/>,
      <md>
        <mrow> (3\mathbf{u} + 4 \mathbf{v}) + (5 \mathbf{u} + 6 \mathbf{v}) \amp= (3 + 5) \mathbf{u} + (4 + 6) \mathbf{v}, </mrow>
        <mrow> 100 (3 \mathbf{u} + 4 \mathbf{v}) \amp= (100 \cdot 3) \mathbf{u} + (100 \cdot 4) \mathbf{v} </mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>
    <p>
      A null space is a subspace: <eg/>, if
      <me>
        3 x_1 + 4 y_1 = 0, \quad 3 x_2 + 4 y_2 = 0
      </me>,
      then
      <md>
        <mrow> 3 (x_1 + x_2) + 4 (y_1 + y_2) \amp= 0, </mrow>
        <mrow> 3 (100 x_1) + 4 (100 y_1) \amp= 0 </mrow>
      </md>.
    </p>
    <reading-questions>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            What are the input and output types of the operation <m>\cdot</m> when it means number multiplication, vector scaling, or vector dot product? In which cases can the <m>\cdot</m> symbol be omitted?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain in your own words how to check something is a linear subspace.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Give some non-examples of a linear subspace.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain in your own words why a span is a subspace. Give examples.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain in your own words why a null space is a subspace. Give examples.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </reading-questions>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Basis and dimension</title>
    <p>
      A basis is a linearly independent spanning set.
    </p>
    <p>
      One procedure to find a basis from a spanning set is to remove vectors one by one. Say
      <me>
        \mathbf{u} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}, \quad \mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix}, \quad \mathbf{w} = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 8 \\ 9 \end{bmatrix}, \quad \mathbf{r} = \begin{bmatrix} 10 \\ 11 \\ 12 \end{bmatrix}
      </me>.
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Now <m>\mathbf{u}</m>, <m>\mathbf{v}</m>, <m>\mathbf{w}</m>, <m>\mathbf{r}</m> are either linearly independent or dependent.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Here they are linearly dependent, and one vector can be expressed as a linear combination of others: <m> \mathbf{w} = 2 \mathbf{v} - \mathbf{u} </m>. So throw <m>\mathbf{w}</m> away.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Now <m>\mathbf{u}</m>, <m>\mathbf{v}</m>, <m>\mathbf{r}</m> are either linearly independent or dependent.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Here they are linearly dependent, and one vector can be expressed as a linear combination of others: <m> \mathbf{r} = 3 \mathbf{v} - 2 \mathbf{u} </m>. So throw <m>\mathbf{r}</m> away.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Now <m>\mathbf{u}</m>, <m>\mathbf{v}</m> are either linearly independent or dependent.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Here they are linearly independent, so <m>\mathbf{u}</m>, <m>\mathbf{v}</m> form a basis.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
      Another equivalent procedure computationally easier is to add vectors one by one. Say <m>\mathbf{u}</m>, <m>\mathbf{v}</m>, <m>\mathbf{w}</m>, <m>\mathbf{r}</m> are the same as above.
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Here <m>\mathbf{u}</m> is not zero. So keep <m>\mathbf{u}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Now <m>\mathbf{u}</m> forms a basis of the span of <m>\mathbf{u}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Here <m>\mathbf{v}</m> is not in the span of <m>\mathbf{u}</m>. So keep <m>\mathbf{v}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Now <m>\mathbf{u}</m>, <m>\mathbf{v}</m> form a basis of the span of <m>\mathbf{u}</m>, <m>\mathbf{v}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Here <m>\mathbf{w}</m> is in the span of <m>\mathbf{u}</m>, <m>\mathbf{v}</m>. So throw <m>\mathbf{w}</m> away.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Now <m>\mathbf{u}</m>, <m>\mathbf{v}</m> form a basis of the span of <m>\mathbf{u}</m>, <m>\mathbf{v}</m>, <m>\mathbf{w}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Here <m>\mathbf{r}</m> is in the span of <m>\mathbf{u}</m>, <m>\mathbf{v}</m>. So throw <m>\mathbf{r}</m> away.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Now <m>\mathbf{u}</m>, <m>\mathbf{v}</m> form a basis of the span of <m>\mathbf{u}</m>, <m>\mathbf{v}</m>, <m>\mathbf{w}</m>, <m>\mathbf{r}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
      Different bases of the same space always have the same size. That number is called the dimension of the space.
    </p>
    <reading-questions>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain in your own words how to find the dimension of a span. Give examples.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain in your own words how to find the dimension of a null space. Give examples.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain in your own words why the size of a spanning set &gt;= the dimension. Give examples of &gt; and =.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain in your own words why the size of a linearly independent set &lt;= the dimension. Give examples of &lt; and =.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </reading-questions>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Coordinates</title>
    <p>
      Since a basis is spanning, any vector can be written as a linear combination of the basis elements. Since a basis is linearly independent, the coefficients are unique: <eg/>, if
      <me>
        x \mathbf{u} + y \mathbf{v} = 3 \mathbf{u} + 4 \mathbf{v}
      </me>,
      then
      <me>
        (x - 3) \mathbf{u} + (y - 4) \mathbf{v} = \mathbf{0}
      </me>.
      The coefficients are called coordinates.
    </p>
    <reading-questions>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain in your own words why coordinates are unique.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            What are the coordinates of a 3-vector under the basis
            <me>
              \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
            </me>?
            What are its coordinates under the basis
            <me>
              \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
            </me>?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose two bases <m>\mathbf{u}</m>, <m>\mathbf{v}</m> and <m>\mathbf{r}</m>, <m>\mathbf{s}</m> are related by
            <md>
              <mrow> \mathbf{u} \amp= \mathbf{r} + 3 \mathbf{s}, </mrow>
              <mrow> \mathbf{v} \amp= 2 \mathbf{r} + 4 \mathbf{s} </mrow>
            </md>.
            What are the coordinates under <m>\mathbf{r}</m>, <m>\mathbf{s}</m> given coordinates under <m>\mathbf{u}</m>, <m>\mathbf{v}</m>? How to find the coordinates under <m>\mathbf{u}</m>, <m>\mathbf{v}</m> given coordinates under <m>\mathbf{r}</m>, <m>\mathbf{s}</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </reading-questions>
  </subsection>
</section>
